  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Coastal Livelihood</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Coastal Integrated Livelihood and Sanitation Project intend to support 3000 vulnerable members of the Aweer community in Kiunga Division. The project seeks to improve their food security, access to potable water, economic activities and sanitation and hygiene practices. Aweers are hunter-gatherers primarily living off the forest resources and limited farming. They are among the smallest most endangered tribes in Kenya. Their livelihood is closely connected with the forest ecosystems. The region in which they inhabit receives unreliable rainfall due to climate change. The little crops which they plant are also destroyed by wild animals because they do not have the capacity and resources to fence their farms which are adjacent to the Boni forest and national game reserve. The project will seek to improve food security through training in new farming technologies and provision of farming inputs. It will also establish women groups and youth groups and train them on how to better market their produce. Moreover, the project will seek to create behavior change among the residents as far as sanitation issues are concerned.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">&#x2022; Training on improved farming methodology to at least 300 subsistence farmers from the Aweer community

&#x2022; Conduct hygiene training to 500 people in the human watering points

&#x2022; Establishing and strengthening of at least 3 women and 3 youth groups for sustainable marketing of their handcrafts and artifacts

&#x2022; Establishment and strengthening of at least 10 Accumulating Savings and Loan Groups(ASCAs)</narrative>
  </description>
